The name has also been interpreted as a merging of the words "Go Ogle", in obvious reference to the undeniable fact that researching the history of, say, Playboy magazine accounts for an inordinately large share of internet traffic. The term appears in [[James Joyce]]'s [[Finnegans Wake]]: "who thought him a Fonar all, feastking of shellies by googling Lovvey" [231.12]. Google then has a rich, haptic connotations - you're not just looking, you're googling when feeling or fondling your way around the Internet. The phrase "to google" has come to be synonymous with "to search for... on the Internet".
